   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>&lt;paulproteus&gt; pythonian4000: I'll do the first rename if you file a bug pointing
out that projects probably need a "URL name" and a "Display name"
* paulproteus does 'em both right now
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; Alrighty
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Done on my end!
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; paulproteus, should the project URL still use the project name?
&lt;paulproteus&gt; I would think it should use a simplified version, just like what
ohloh.net does.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Like a WordPress blog post, projects should have a "slug"
(URL-safe name) and a "title" (long, flowery thing)
&lt;paulproteus&gt; e.g. "debian" and "Debian GNU/Linux"
&lt;paulproteus&gt; That's what I'm thinkinkg
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; Well the way OpenHatch handles URLs, pretty much anything is
URL-safe, like unescaped spaces
&lt;paulproteus&gt; It's true, but for e.g. copy-pasting. Well it's just one idea; we
can discuss it later (-:
&lt;paulproteus&gt; The reason, though, is that when we import projects from far away,
we're not consistent about if we use the URL-name or the project name, from the
remote service.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Plus re-titling projects, this way, could be done without breaking
URLs, so we could make it part of the project edit interface.
&lt;paulproteus&gt; +projedit/
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; So the current Project name becomes the URL name and Display
name will be what appears in strings (and can maybe default to the same as the
URL one)
&lt;paulproteus&gt; Yeah, I think that's the best way to do it.
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; We will just need to make sure it integrates properly with the
bug importing stuff - since the projects currently use names rather than Foreign
keys to link, they will need to be checked.
&lt;pythonian4000&gt; cf. <a href="issue161">issue161</a></pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
